Pour the @water{300%ml} into a large #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When
boiling, add in and dissolve half the @chicken stock powder{1}, then stir in the
@basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan.
Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat and set aside (still covered)
for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

== Chicken and Sauce ==

Meanwhile, put the @diced chicken thigh{260%g} in a #mixing bowl{} and add half
the @cornflour{20%g} and half the @sesame oil{24%ml}. Season with @salt{} and
@ground black pepper{} and mix well with your hands. Leave to one side.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

In a #small bowl{}, mix the remaining cornflour with 1tsp of @water{100%ml} per
person. Set aside.

Boil your #kettle{}. Trim the @spring onion{2} and thinly slice. Zest the
@lemon{2} then chop in half. Halve the @red chilli{1/2}, deseed and finely chop.
In the #measuring jug{}, combine the boiling water with the remaining stock
powder and sesame oil, a pinch of lemon zest, the lemon juice, @soy sauce{25%ml},
@rice vinegar{15%ml}, @sugar{1.5%tbsp} and a pinch of chilli. This is your sauce.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} or #wok{} on high heat. When hot,
add the chicken and stir-fry until just turning golden, ~{3-4%minutes}. Transfer
to a #bowl{} and set aside.

Carefully wipe out the pan (it'll be hot!) and return to medium heat. Add the
sauce and bring to a simmer then whisk in the cornflour mixture, making sure
there are no lumps.

Return the chicken to the pan along with the @mangetout{150%g} and half the
spring onion. Simmer until the chicken is cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Season to taste with salt and pepper if needed.

> TIP: If you like things zingy, add a pinch more lemon zest.

== To Serve ==

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and serve in #bowls{}. Spoon the lemon chicken
over the top and finish with a sprinkling of remaining spring onion and the
chilli (if you want a bit more kick!). Enjoy!